	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Main seafood eco-labelling scheme is in crisis, say scientists </h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The world's most established fisheries certifier is failing on its promises as rapidly as it gains prominence, according to leading fisheries experts. Established in 1997 by the World Wildlife Fund and Unilever, one of the world's largest fish retailers, the Marine Stewardship Council (MSC) has been helping consumers eat fish from certified fisheries. In an opinion piece published in the latest issue of the scientific magazine <i>Nature</i>, six fisheries researchers, including the founding father of fisheries science, Sidney Holt, object to many of the MSC's procedures and certification of certain species.</p><p>‘The MSC is supposed to be a solution, but a lot of what they do has turned against biology in favour of bureaucracy’ says the lead author. The scientists argue that fisheries that are being heavily depleted, reliant on high-impact methods such as bottom trawling and that are not destined for human consumption should be excluded from certification: ‘The MSC should not certify fisheries that are not demonstrably sustainable, fisheries that use high-impact methods such as bottom trawling and/or fisheries that are not destined for human consumption,’ says one of the authors.</p><p>The authors also note that the current certification system, which relies on for-profit consultants and which could cost as much as $150,000, presents a potential conflict of interest and discriminates against small-scale fisheries and fisheries from developing countries - most of which use highly-selective and sustainable techniques. They point out that ‘the failure of the MSC hurts the fish populations that are not sustainably taken and their ecosystems; it deprives the public of an opportunity to make a meaningful choice and it damages those fisheries that are well managed - this is especially important for those sustainable small-scale fisheries competing with the giants that buy certifications they have not earned … Unless MSC goes under major reform, there are better, more effective ways to spend the certifier's $13-million annual budget to help the oceans …’ </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Article in <i>Nature</i>, ‘Seafood stewardship in crisis’, September 2010, quoted in <i>Science Daily</i>, 10 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/09/100901132159.htm" target="_self">http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/09/100901132159.htm</a></p><p>MSC website:</p><p>
<a href="http://www.msc.org/" target="_self">http://www.msc.org/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Ecolabelling schemes all too often suffer from a lack of transparency. So far very few ACP fisheries have been certified or are under assessment, in South Africa, Madagascar, Suriname, some Pacific islands etc. It will be important to ensure that no ecolabelling schemes lead to discrimination against developing countries, as this would eventually undermine their credibility. </p>
		</div>
		
